# HTML Text

## What is HTML Text?

HTML text refers to the content displayed on a webpage using text-related HTML elements.

These elements help browsers understand the meaning and structure of textual content such as:

- Headings
- Paragraphs
- Bold text
- Italic text
- Underlined text
- Highlighted text
- Superscript/Subscript text
- Quotations
- Code snippets

---

## Why Do HTML Text Elements Exist?

Imagine if all webpage text looked like this:

```
Welcome to our website this is the title this is important text this is a quotation this is computer code.
```

The browser would not know:

- Which text is a heading.
- Which text is important.
- Which text is quoted.
- Which text represents code.

HTML text elements provide **meaning (semantics)** to text.

---

# Headings

Used to define titles and section headings.

## Syntax

```html
<h1>Main Heading</h1>
<h2>Sub Heading</h2>
<h3>Section Heading</h3>
<h4>Sub Section</h4>
<h5>Minor Heading</h5>
<h6>Smallest Heading</h6>
```

## Example

```html
<h1>HTML Tutorial</h1>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<h3>Basics</h3>
```

## Output

Largest text:
```
HTML Tutorial
```

Smaller text:
```
Introduction
Basics
```

## Best Practice

Use headings based on document structure.

Do NOT use them only to make text bigger.

---

# Paragraph

Used to represent blocks of text.

## Syntax

```html
<p>This is a paragraph.</p>
```

## Example

```html
<p>
HTML is used to structure webpages.
</p>
```

## Output

Displays a paragraph with spacing before and after it.

---

# Line Break

Moves text to the next line.

## Syntax

```html
<br>
```

## Example

```html
Hello<br>
World
```

## Output

```
Hello
World
```

---

# Horizontal Rule

Creates a horizontal line.

## Syntax

```html
<hr>
```

## Example

```html
<p>Chapter 1</p>
<hr>
<p>Chapter 2</p>
```

---

# Bold Text

Makes text bold without emphasizing importance.

## Syntax

```html
<b>Bold Text</b>
```

## Example

```html
<b>Welcome</b>
```

---

# Strong Text

Indicates important text.

Browsers usually display it as bold.

## Syntax

```html
<strong>Important</strong>
```

## Difference

```html
<b>Visual styling only</b>

<strong>Important meaning</strong>
```

---

# Italic Text

Displays text in italic style.

## Syntax

```html
<i>Italic Text</i>
```

---

# Emphasized Text

Indicates stress or emphasis.

Usually displayed in italics.

## Syntax

```html
<em>Very Important</em>
```

## Difference

```html
<i>Visual italic</i>

<em>Semantic emphasis</em>
```

---

# Underlined Text

## Syntax

```html
<u>Underlined</u>
```

## Example

```html
<u>Notice</u>
```

---

# Marked Text

Highlights text.

## Syntax

```html
<mark>Highlighted</mark>
```

## Example

```html
<p>This is <mark>important</mark>.</p>
```

---

# Small Text

Displays smaller text.

## Syntax

```html
<small>Small text</small>
```

## Example

```html
<small>Terms and Conditions apply.</small>
```

---

# Deleted Text

Shows removed content.

Usually displayed with a strike-through.

## Syntax

```html
<del>Old Price</del>
```

## Example

```html
<del>$100</del>
$80
```

## Output

```
$100   ← struck through
$80
```

---

# Inserted Text

Represents newly inserted text.

Usually underlined.

## Syntax

```html
<ins>New Content</ins>
```

---

# Subscript Text

Appears below normal text.

## Syntax

```html
<sub>Text</sub>
```

## Example

```html
H<sub>2</sub>O
```

## Output

```
H₂O
```

---

# Superscript Text

Appears above normal text.

## Syntax

```html
<sup>Text</sup>
```

## Example

```html
x<sup>2</sup>
```

## Output

```
x²
```

---

# Quotations

## Short Quotations

Uses `<q>`.

### Example

```html
<p>He said, <q>Hello World</q></p>
```

### Output

```
He said, "Hello World"
```

---

## Block Quotations

Uses `<blockquote>`.

### Example

```html
<blockquote>
Success is not final.
Failure is not fatal.
</blockquote>
```

---

# Abbreviations

Uses `<abbr>`.

## Example

```html
<abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">
HTML
</abbr>
```

When hovered:

```
HyperText Markup Language
```

---

# Address

Defines contact information.

## Example

```html
<address>
John Doe<br>
Chennai<br>
India
</address>
```

---

# Code Text

Displays programming code.

## Syntax

```html
<code>
print("Hello")
</code>
```

## Example

```html
<p>Use <code>print()</code> to display output.</p>
```

---

# Preformatted Text

Preserves spaces and line breaks.

## Syntax

```html
<pre>
Line 1
    Line 2
        Line 3
</pre>
```

## Output

Spacing remains exactly the same.

---

# Text Elements Comparison

| Element | Purpose | Semantic Meaning |
|----------|----------|-------------------|
| `<b>` | Bold | No |
| `<strong>` | Important text | Yes |
| `<i>` | Italic | No |
| `<em>` | Emphasized text | Yes |
| `<del>` | Deleted text | Yes |
| `<ins>` | Inserted text | Yes |
| `<sub>` | Subscript | Yes |
| `<sup>` | Superscript | Yes |
| `<code>` | Code snippet | Yes |
| `<mark>` | Highlight | Yes |

---

# Mental Model

Think of HTML text elements as labels attached to text.

Example:

```
Text
 ↓
Heading?
Paragraph?
Important?
Code?
Quotation?
Chemical Formula?
```

The browser uses these labels to understand how the text should be interpreted.

---

# Best Practices

- Use `<strong>` instead of `<b>` for important content.
- Use `<em>` instead of `<i>` when emphasis is intended.
- Structure pages using proper heading hierarchy.
- Use semantic text elements whenever possible.
- Use `<code>` for programming examples.
- Avoid using formatting tags purely for visual styling; CSS should handle appearance.

---

